WEBVTT

00:00.898 --> 00:03.500
Well, good morning, Menlo Church, and welcome.

00:03.700 --> 00:19.014
Welcome back to our series called I Am, where we're kind of walking through this season called Lent in the Week leading up to Easter as a part of our kind of personal and collective preparation of celebration for the resurrection of Jesus.

00:19.474 --> 00:27.981
One of the ways that we do that and take part in this season together is through a daily devotional guide that we've created that parallels the teaching series.

00:28.462 --> 00:30.884
If you haven't started that, I haven't downloaded or gotten into it,

00:30.864 --> 00:32.025
yet is there still time?

00:32.406 --> 00:35.469
You can find it at menlo.church.connect.

00:35.529 --> 00:37.892
You can walk through that yourself or with your community.

00:38.472 --> 00:40.494
We'd be honored to have you join us.

00:41.175 --> 00:47.362
Today is such a fun weekend across all of our campuses in San Mateo, Menlo Park, Mountain View, Saratoga.

00:47.382 --> 00:55.090
We have students who are helping out in some fun and exciting ways to remind all of us that they aren't just the church of tomorrow.

00:55.110 --> 00:56.351
They're the church of today.

00:56.732 --> 01:00.836
And in a lot of our campuses, the students that are helping out, they're doing the things they do

01:00.816 --> 01:05.822
every weekend because the next generation really is the church of today here at Menlo all the time.

01:05.862 --> 01:08.024
We just wanted to spotlight it uniquely this weekend.

01:08.725 --> 01:11.969
In addition, we are celebrating baptisms this weekend.

01:12.329 --> 01:22.781
Near the end of our services, people will publicly declare their faith in Jesus through baptism, which was modeled by Jesus as a way of making personal faith public.

01:23.021 --> 01:26.686
And some of those people have actually recorded part of their story to share with you.

01:26.706 --> 01:30.450
I'm really excited for you to experience it near the end of our time together.

01:30.914 --> 01:36.219
Also, I want to name something that some of you, you came in today expecting primarily to spectate.

01:36.339 --> 01:37.700
You came in to observe.

01:37.760 --> 01:38.260
And that's great.

01:38.280 --> 01:39.241
We're glad that you're here.

01:39.782 --> 01:47.428
But over the course of the message, at some point, you may feel compelled by God to participate, actually, to even get baptized.

01:47.568 --> 01:52.853
And as crazy as that sounds, it happens every one of these weekends across Menlo.

01:53.213 --> 01:59.419
And so because of that, we want to make sure that we never stand in the way of what God may do in your life in these moments.

01:59.479 --> 02:00.900
And so we have fresh

02:00.880 --> 02:05.185
Shorts, shirts, ready for you, a place for you to change.

02:05.365 --> 02:13.513
If you feel prompted by God at some point that you know, like, man, I'm peeling pulled to this public commitment of a personal faith.

02:13.874 --> 02:16.697
Maybe you feel like I just need a hard reset in my life right now.

02:17.278 --> 02:19.760
Please don't leave without taking that step.

02:19.780 --> 02:26.367
I'll give you some instructions at the end, but we want to remove every barrier possible for you to experience that.

02:27.008 --> 02:30.852
Now, before we dive into our time together, I'm going to pray for us, and we're

02:30.832 --> 02:43.966
We're all sort of reeling and processing in real time what's happening on the other side of the world in Iran and the strikes that took place there and then ultimately the rising conflict that's taking place in the region.

02:44.507 --> 02:55.258
And this is one of those times where we're just reminded that oftentimes we come to a moment like this with very different perspectives, at least in part because we have very different sources of information.

02:55.298 --> 03:00.804
And so it's a reminder not to be informed or formed

03:00.784 --> 03:09.673
to spiritually, by an algorithm or by a one-sided news take, continue to have wide-ranging conversations, pursue the best information.

03:10.214 --> 03:29.134
The algorithm, no matter what it's telling you, it cannot pray for the people in Iran, it cannot pray for the region that's impacted, it cannot pray for our world leaders, and it cannot grieve the pain and loss that people are feeling, not just over the last few days, but over the last several months of atrocities that have taken place in that region.

03:29.495 --> 03:30.756
And so we're going to do that.

03:30.736 --> 03:32.798
Our responsibility, God's asked us to do that.

03:33.159 --> 03:44.190
And if you don't know this, Iran is actually one of the places that has the fastest growing underground church of followers of Jesus in a heavily persecuted region in the entire world.

03:44.671 --> 03:50.978
And we've watched thousands of them give their life for their faith in the most recent months.

03:51.478 --> 04:00.708
And we're gonna be praying in just a moment that God would use that church, his people, not only to provide them safety, not only to provide them a voice, but that his kingdom

04:00.688 --> 04:08.535
His will would be done in Tehran, in Iran, in the Middle East, and around the world because his church is given a unique opportunity to do that.

04:08.936 --> 04:16.823
And so, again, challenge the algorithm, challenge the new sources that you receive to go get the best information that you might be most informed.

04:16.843 --> 04:22.028
And remember what the information sources you are reading and receiving can do and what they can't do.

04:22.388 --> 04:26.412
And let's make sure we do our part to bring the hurts of this world to the heart of heaven.

04:26.812 --> 04:28.914
Would you pray with me now that we might do that together?

04:30.114 --> 04:35.314
God, we really do grieve atrocities on scales we can't imagine.

04:35.650 --> 04:41.795
It's not lost on us, God, that we look around a campus like the one we're at today or logged online.

04:41.855 --> 04:44.838
And we're so grateful to be able to worship.

04:44.858 --> 04:47.040
We're so grateful to be able to open your word.

04:47.080 --> 04:50.183
We're so grateful to be able to have moments of celebration as a church.

04:50.863 --> 04:54.787
But God, I'm reminded that with those who grieve, with those who weep, we grieve, we weep.

04:54.887 --> 04:58.530
And so we think about our brothers and sisters in Iran right now.

04:58.590 --> 05:02.954
We think about people who don't know you yet, but they're made in your image with infinite dignity, value, and worth.

05:02.994 --> 05:05.636
And they're living under unparalleled

05:05.616 --> 05:07.058
and threats of violence.

05:07.699 --> 05:09.562
And so, God, would you bring peace to that region?

05:09.602 --> 05:14.729
Would you quickly de-escalate and stabilize the government in that place?

05:14.769 --> 05:19.936
Would you help world leaders to make decisions that are empowered by wisdom, not from them, but from you?

05:20.557 --> 05:26.426
God, we pray that your kingdom would come, that your will would be done in Tehran, in Iran, in the Middle East, and around the world.

05:27.347 --> 05:35.218
God, would you use your church to have a voice that is inexplicable, to have hands that are supernatural in their capacity to care for those who need it?

05:35.906 --> 05:43.493
And God in our own lives help us to remember that as big as the world is and as much hurt and pain as there is around it, there's hurt in our life.

05:43.533 --> 05:44.494
There's pain in our life.

05:44.534 --> 05:46.076
There are circumstances for us too.

05:46.136 --> 05:49.499
And help us not to just pretend those aren't there or to run.

05:49.539 --> 05:55.565
Remind us over these next few minutes what it looks like to sit with you in them, even the difficult parts.

05:56.406 --> 05:58.568
Thank you for the goodness of your hand in our lives.

05:58.588 --> 06:00.089
Thank you for the grace that's available.

06:00.109 --> 06:01.230
Help us to remember it now.

06:02.131 --> 06:04.914
Not only in our lives, but the lives of those who need it all around the world.

06:05.442 --> 06:06.156
in Jesus' name.

06:07.258 --> 06:07.666
Amen.

06:09.122 --> 06:14.947
So as we get started, I want to kind of think about a little bit of the unique facets of our region.

06:15.007 --> 06:21.112
We are kind of like hardwired into the way we think about life, through the way we think about technology.

06:21.132 --> 06:22.133
It's kind of everywhere.

06:22.153 --> 06:28.319
When somebody tells you in Silicon Valley that they work in healthcare, in my mind, I'm like, yeah, but like technology healthcare, right?

06:28.339 --> 06:32.462
Like technology is the first part of every answer, a little bit in people's mind.

06:32.502 --> 06:39.108
And in computing, there's this thing called RAM, which provides for your active workspace.

06:39.088 --> 06:43.292
of memory that lets you keep working and leave things open in the background.

06:43.313 --> 06:50.200
It's why some of you have 75 Google Chrome tabs open right now on a computer that you're not at, right?

06:50.740 --> 06:56.246
For a long time in Silicon Valley, our solution to a lagging system was really easy.

06:56.266 --> 07:01.051
You just added more RAM so that you could run more things in the background.

07:01.071 --> 07:04.956
But right now, the solution is really not that readily available.

07:05.356 --> 07:09.060
With the explosion of commercial AI systems, RAM has become increasingly

07:09.040 --> 07:18.577
and increasingly expensive as a result, and the commercial customers have made it more difficult for regular people to get their hands on it.

07:18.637 --> 07:22.885
And the greater the demand these systems have, we'll create that problem even more.

07:23.426 --> 07:29.036
Not only has that happened on the technology side, I think that's actually happened for you and me too.

07:29.076 --> 07:32.242
We've hit the same wall regarding our lives.

07:32.802 --> 07:36.848
As a matter of fact, we don't close any tabs in our personal lives, in our inner worlds, either.

07:37.169 --> 07:39.192
We don't switch tasks, we just add.

07:39.753 --> 07:44.900
And then in the midst of that, we try to upgrade our personal RAM, our internal capacity.

07:44.940 --> 07:47.324
We try to think about how we hack or optimize.

07:47.344 --> 07:51.631
For some of you, you have optimized sleep to an unbelievable level.

07:51.771 --> 07:56.498
Others of you, I heard, are eating or like drinking mushrooms in your coffee, which is

07:56.770 --> 07:58.434
wild, right?

07:58.454 --> 08:04.649
We become completely obsessed with sheer willpower to keep our background processes running.

08:04.710 --> 08:08.278
We're not always paying attention to how many are still running.

08:08.800 --> 08:13.010
But that approach is breaking us because we're not machines.

08:13.474 --> 08:18.320
See, when the load gets too heavy, our cultural instinct in that moment is to pray a prayer like this.

08:18.440 --> 08:21.263
Even if you're not a person of faith, I bet you've prayed a prayer like this.

08:21.604 --> 08:27.571
God, please give me the strength to keep up the unsustainable and unchecked level of commitment in my life.

08:28.532 --> 08:32.156
I mean, we don't say it with those words, we say different words, they're nicer, but that's what we're praying.

08:32.957 --> 08:40.626
But the questions that we're gonna be forced to consider today is what if God isn't adding capacity in your life on purpose?

08:40.962 --> 08:44.727
What if he's actually crashing the system for your good?

08:45.828 --> 08:57.564
See, most of us, when we feel that impulse, when we feel like the responsibility, the load is heavier than the limit, maybe not physically, but emotionally and spiritually, we run, we retreat from the thing we feel.

08:58.225 --> 09:05.234
Sometimes our running looks like numbing with behaviors that we use to disengage from feelings of pain or exhaustion.

09:05.538 --> 09:11.888
But believe it or not, what our lesson for us today that we're gonna learn is that faith grows in wrestling, not retreating.

09:12.329 --> 09:21.124
You can't run away from the work that God needs to do in your life, and the longer you run, the more you retreat, the more wrestling is waiting for you on the other side.

09:21.965 --> 09:29.938
Last week, we spent time in the desert with Moses, and this week, we are looking at his great, great grandfather, Jacob.

09:30.050 --> 09:45.522
Now, when Moses was called to lead the nation of Israel, it's kind of a wild, full circle moment because that entire nation, Israel, was named after the new name that God gave Jacob in a really unique moment of his life that we're going to explore together today.

09:45.890 --> 09:50.701
But unlike Moses, Jacob has way fewer pop culture references.

09:51.382 --> 09:54.269
So you might be coming into the story with less to go on.

09:54.570 --> 09:56.955
And so I want to give you a little bit of a heads up.

09:56.975 --> 10:01.746
Jacob, if you looked at his resume, it kind of was like a Silicon Valley entrepreneur.

10:01.826 --> 10:07.495
For the time, your name and what it meant carried a lot of significance in the culture that he lived.

10:07.535 --> 10:12.262
And his name means the grasps, which he did literally in the womb.

10:12.603 --> 10:15.928
It also means deceiver, which he did the moment he left the womb.

10:16.108 --> 10:23.760
And before you get mad about it, right, we see it play out over and over again in his life, and it provides lessons for us in ours.

10:24.120 --> 10:30.450
From day one, Jacob learns to run on a survival and manipulation pattern.

10:30.594 --> 10:36.620
The framework and operating system of his life was just about scheming and running over and over and over again.

10:37.161 --> 10:41.406
When Jacob's brother Esau was starving, Jacob extorted him for his birthright.

10:42.066 --> 10:45.990
And in the middle of a culture where that was brilliant, it was also brutal.

10:46.651 --> 10:55.721
Later on in his life, he would put on goat skins on his arms to feel like his brother, which part of me is like, how hairy was Esau?

10:55.761 --> 10:56.882
That's wild.

10:57.730 --> 11:07.614
And then he would go on to use this deception to trick his blind, aging, dying father into giving him the family blessing that was rightly reserved for Esau.

11:07.654 --> 11:09.458
And then he ran again.

11:09.826 --> 11:17.796
And after escaping the very well-deserved punishment that he would have received from his brother, he ends up with his uncle Laban, where he finally meets his match.

11:17.836 --> 11:21.981
And he can't orchestrate or work out a specific outcome the way he had in the past.

11:22.462 --> 11:28.649
He endured two decades of grueling labor at the hands of his uncle, manipulation, family drama.

11:29.030 --> 11:35.538
And at the very end of that, he finally gets to leave with massive wealth, but no peace.

11:35.746 --> 11:40.439
See, he was a self-made man who continued to spiral into self-destruction.

11:40.820 --> 11:47.338
He had decades of dirt, desperation that everything about him when you read his story is looking to be washed clean.

11:47.358 --> 11:50.066
Like, what would it look like for him to get to the other side of this?

11:50.498 --> 12:05.697
And after all of this decades later, Jacob is heading home when he hears that his brother Esau turns out has not forgotten about how he left in the first place and is headed to meet his brother with 400 men who were not the welcoming committee.

12:06.378 --> 12:14.729
And Jacob's system, the way he has lived his life, the way he has retreated over and over and over again, that system finally crashes.

12:15.089 --> 12:18.994
He's alone, he's out of options, and he's running on empty.

12:19.394 --> 12:22.640
This moment of desperation is where we join the story today.

12:22.700 --> 12:25.345
And I'm gonna read the passage for our story today.

12:25.365 --> 12:28.931
It's a little bit longer passage than we usually read at one spot.

12:28.951 --> 12:34.000
And so my encouragement to you is whatever you need to do to really listen, to give God's word your attention, do that.

12:34.361 --> 12:37.346
Maybe that's opening your own Bible and opening to this passage.

12:37.366 --> 12:43.858
Maybe it's closing your eyes, looking at the screen, whatever you need to do that we might be able to hear together the word of God.

12:44.066 --> 12:44.887
Here's how it starts.

12:44.947 --> 12:53.816
It says, the same night he rose and took his two wives, his two female servants, and his 11 children, and crossed the forward of the jabok.

12:54.476 --> 13:00.002
He took them and sent them across the stream, and everything else that he had in Jacob was left alone.

13:00.722 --> 13:03.745
And a man wrestled with him until the breaking of the day.

13:04.446 --> 13:12.754
When the man saw that he did not prevail against Jacob, he touched his hip socket, and Jacob's hip socket was put out of place as he wrestled with him.

13:13.122 --> 13:16.226
And then he said, let me go for the day has broken.

13:16.286 --> 13:19.811
But Jacob said, I will not let you go unless you bless me.

13:20.532 --> 13:22.074
And he said to him, what is your name?

13:22.455 --> 13:24.017
And he said, Jacob.

13:24.758 --> 13:27.982
Then he said, your name shall no longer be called Jacob, but Israel.

13:28.723 --> 13:32.408
For you have striven with God and with men and have prevailed.

13:33.129 --> 13:35.112
Then Jacob asked him, please tell me your name.

13:35.352 --> 13:37.115
But he said, why is it that you ask my name?

13:37.976 --> 13:39.698
And there he blessed him.

13:40.066 --> 13:47.638
So Jacob called the name of the place Penil saying, for I have seen God face to face, and yet my life has been delivered.

13:48.400 --> 13:54.169
The sun rose upon him as he passed Penil limping because of his hip.

13:55.251 --> 14:01.101
Now we're gonna look at this from three different places, three benefits of what happens when you and I stay in the fight when we wrestle instead of retreat.

14:01.121 --> 14:04.466
But before we do that, we need to acknowledge that this scene is wild.

14:04.834 --> 14:10.343
This is one of those stories that if you grew up in church, they sort of like go buy this one pretty fast in Sunday school.

14:10.784 --> 14:11.545
Like, what happened?

14:11.706 --> 14:12.747
Ah, let's move to the next one.

14:13.188 --> 14:17.555
It's just the one that we have to sort of slow down and go, what just happened?

14:17.656 --> 14:19.579
Because God didn't send a counselor.

14:20.040 --> 14:21.262
He didn't send a contract.

14:21.282 --> 14:22.324
He didn't send a scroll.

14:22.364 --> 14:25.028
He didn't send like a conflict resolution plan.

14:25.469 --> 14:29.015
He shows up personally in the dirt and wrestles Jacob.

14:30.117 --> 14:30.898
That's the story.

14:31.618 --> 14:36.866
Now wrestling, if you've never thought about it, it is the most intimate form of combat sports.

14:37.407 --> 14:41.052
You're sweating, you're grappling, remember the name, Jacob and what it means?

14:41.473 --> 14:55.154
You're breathing the same air and right there, God met Jacob, not as a distant judge, but as an opponent in the dirt of his decisions and the literal dirt that he found himself in as a part of decades leading to this moment of isolation.

14:55.554 --> 15:05.690
Jacob had been running, had been retreating his entire life, but for the first time ever, he was in a spot where he has nowhere to run.

15:05.750 --> 15:15.725
Retreat is no longer an option, with a brother coming from one direction with a few hundred friends who did not have nice intentions, and an angelic messenger ready to wrestle him.

15:15.925 --> 15:21.554
Finally, he has no choice but to deal with the reality of his situation.

15:21.634 --> 15:26.703
It's at this point that we see the first of the three benefits of staying in the fight in our lives.

15:27.124 --> 15:29.889
And the first is that the fight brings an invitation to honesty.

15:29.929 --> 15:31.692
It did it for Jacob and it does it for you and me.

15:32.313 --> 15:42.191
Jacob, he was used to wearing lots of masks, lots of layers in his life that allowed him to manipulate and triangulate and get what he wants, or in some cases goat skins to be able to do that.

15:42.832 --> 15:44.114
But in a wrestling match,

15:44.514 --> 15:45.435
You can't fake it.

15:45.515 --> 15:47.118
People see who you really are.

15:47.298 --> 15:50.082
Like, you're too close for them to see something else.

15:50.102 --> 15:52.125
You can't manipulate someone into a headlock.

15:52.425 --> 15:55.209
You actually have to be close to them.

15:55.910 --> 15:59.475
God wrestles Jacob to the point that he is beyond exhausted.

15:59.535 --> 16:02.319
His self-reliance can no longer even be an option.

16:02.860 --> 16:04.563
And his resources are long gone.

16:05.103 --> 16:09.810
His masks and his layers, just like Moses was last week, have all been stripped away.

16:10.402 --> 16:14.669
And that's exactly a picture actually that we see when people choose to get baptized.

16:15.210 --> 16:28.212
What we see in baptism is God telling other people through you that it's okay to stop pretending that the polite polished polity of our religiosity is meeting the real need of people that are facing real challenges in their lives.

16:28.994 --> 16:36.306
That God can handle your honest grief, your exhaustion, and the tough questions that you have that don't have easy answers.

16:36.674 --> 16:39.458
because you can't fake it in a wrestling ring.

16:39.478 --> 16:40.859
This is not WWF.

16:41.701 --> 16:46.106
And baptisms, somebody at one of the services was like, wait a second, WWF's not real?

16:46.287 --> 16:47.808
Sorry if I burst that bubble for you.

16:48.790 --> 16:55.559
Baptism is a reminder that no one starts their story of baptism or their story with God with personal strength.

16:56.239 --> 17:04.370
It's actually God's story with us that starts with wrestling in each of us, admitting where we fall short, admitting that we need Him.

17:04.770 --> 17:06.673
And that's exactly where we find Jacob.

17:07.354 --> 17:11.139
He's been wrestling in the darkness for hours, which feels wild to me.

17:11.540 --> 17:14.223
I think it would take me seconds to get tired wrestling.

17:14.764 --> 17:15.765
The masks are gone.

17:15.846 --> 17:17.027
He's completely drained.

17:17.488 --> 17:24.658
But just as he reaches this point where he is at the absolute end of himself, verse 25, shows us something interesting.

17:24.678 --> 17:33.170
It says, when the man saw that he did not prevail against Jacob, he touched his hip socket and Jacob's hip was put out of joint as he wrestled with him.

17:33.410 --> 17:37.957
Now we need to pause here and just have a moment of intellectual honesty about what we just read.

17:38.498 --> 17:42.324
Does that really say that God couldn't overpower Jacob?

17:43.245 --> 17:44.086
Is that what we're reading?

17:45.048 --> 17:46.390
Now think about that for a minute.

17:46.891 --> 17:57.828
Like a moment where the creator of the universe is to the point where he can't pin an exhausted aging shepherd.

17:58.088 --> 17:59.410
Is that what we're reading in the passage?

18:00.130 --> 18:04.476
Well, if God wanted to, we all know this, he could have vaporized Jacob with a single thought.

18:05.758 --> 18:06.459
So why didn't he?

18:07.600 --> 18:14.229
Theologians, they refer to what we're reading as something called a Theophany, which is a pre-incarnate appearing of Jesus in the flesh.

18:14.690 --> 18:18.956
He shows up in the world before he would be born as a baby 2,000 years ago.

18:19.096 --> 18:26.706
Think about for a minute what it's like for a loving father wrestling on the living room floor with a toddler who loves wrestling.

18:27.138 --> 18:32.206
The dad could easily overpower the kid, but the goal isn't destruction, at least not for the dad.

18:32.226 --> 18:36.733
I have had toddlers, the destruction, the plan for them for me, I think, is destruction.

18:36.753 --> 18:40.419
But as the dad, the goal is not destruction, it's connection.

18:40.479 --> 18:46.549
The father limits his own strength to let the child exert theirs.

18:47.290 --> 18:54.482
He lets the child exhaust his or her tantrum, feel their limits, and eventually yield.

18:55.042 --> 19:03.075
Now, God, in this passage specifically, I believe, restricts his divine power to make space for Jacob's strength, agency, and realization.

19:03.756 --> 19:07.982
God allows himself to lose the physical match in order to win Jacob's heart.

19:08.744 --> 19:15.314
He lets Jacob burn out of his human strength, and oftentimes with us, I think that's exactly what it takes.

19:15.874 --> 19:28.923
Part of the way that we read about God in the Old Testament is something called anthropomorphism, where human language is used to describe how God works, but it is always limited because we are finite limited beings exploring an infinite God.

19:28.943 --> 19:32.370
And I believe that's another aspect of what we're seeing right here.

19:32.770 --> 19:37.898
that collision of human exhaustion and God's grace and the infinite nature of a perfect God.

19:38.579 --> 19:47.172
It gets us actually to the second benefit, not just that there's honesty that we have an invitation for, but that the fight actually brings a limp of blessing.

19:47.933 --> 19:49.496
The fight brings a limp of blessing.

19:49.536 --> 19:53.682
See, when God touches Jacob's hip, he permanently dislocates it.

19:54.018 --> 19:57.662
We usually assume that an encounter with God will leave us feeling invincible.

19:57.682 --> 19:58.303
That's what we hope.

19:58.383 --> 20:05.951
Like some of you, you came to church this weekend because you wanted an encounter with God and you thought, I didn't know that a dislocated hip was one of the possibilities, right?

20:07.172 --> 20:11.937
See, we usually assume that an encounter with God will always leave us feeling better, invincible on the other side.

20:11.977 --> 20:14.419
But Jacob, he walks away from this fight with a permanent limp.

20:14.560 --> 20:14.800
Why?

20:14.840 --> 20:20.626
Because the limp means that Jacob can no longer run.

20:21.410 --> 20:32.280
means that all those things that he's been following, all those patterns that he's used to retreat, to get out of the situation that oftentimes he's put himself in, all of those resources are gone now.

20:33.281 --> 20:39.787
His primary defense mechanism, the algorithm that he had relied on his entire life, has been completely dismantled.

20:40.508 --> 20:49.536
And God knew that it would take this level of intervention for his life to really change and for the plan of God to actually be embraced for the future through his life.

20:50.157 --> 20:51.218
And if we're honest,

20:51.490 --> 20:58.197
Most of us, we don't mind the idea of an encounter with God, even if you're not a person of faith, as long as we don't have a limp afterwards.

20:58.978 --> 21:05.164
We like altar moments, we don't like altered states, we like breakthrough, but we do not want the breaking that might come first.

21:05.865 --> 21:13.552
We want to encounter God right now, but we have not counted the cost of that encounter, and I'll just tell you not to scare you, but to let you know there is always a cost to the encounter.

21:14.413 --> 21:19.218
It's for your good, you need it, I need it, but we often don't want it, we've been retreating from it.

21:19.810 --> 21:21.874
Sometimes the limp is a blessing.

21:22.956 --> 21:26.121
For me, the limp actually didn't happen beside a river.

21:26.502 --> 21:27.905
It happened on a football field.

21:27.945 --> 21:33.094
In high school, I blew my knees out playing football twice because I'm a slow learner.

21:33.435 --> 21:38.904
And in the midst of that, I wasn't wrestling with God about how he could do this.

21:38.924 --> 21:40.828
I wasn't yelling on the field, why God?

21:40.908 --> 21:44.274
No, no, no, I was just upset that my Friday nights just became open.

21:45.346 --> 21:48.810
But looking back, football wasn't really the problem of what was going on.

21:48.850 --> 21:51.133
Football, it didn't pull me away from God.

21:51.813 --> 21:53.856
What I was letting it turn me into did.

21:54.677 --> 22:01.865
See, I had sensed a call from God when I was younger about a pull toward orienting my life around him in a specific direction for my life.

22:01.905 --> 22:04.728
But football, it gave me a different script to follow.

22:05.429 --> 22:09.714
Identity through dominance, value through performance, approval through applause.

22:10.415 --> 22:12.978
Now, none of that is inherently evil.

22:13.154 --> 22:19.664
The sport wasn't sinful, but I could feel myself becoming someone God hadn't called me to be.

22:20.125 --> 22:23.770
More ego, more image, more edge, less Jesus.

22:24.652 --> 22:30.681
So when my knees gave out, I didn't do some massive, dramatic, holy wrestling match with God.

22:31.843 --> 22:32.364
I retreated.

22:33.125 --> 22:38.994
I pivoted into theater, which at 16 was like a pretty weird transition, right?

22:39.522 --> 22:41.106
shoulder pads to stage makeup.

22:41.166 --> 22:42.609
It was a different bag.

22:42.669 --> 22:43.792
I was carrying with me, right?

22:44.654 --> 22:46.778
I wasn't shaking my fist at heaven.

22:46.859 --> 22:47.580
I was drifting.

22:47.721 --> 22:52.211
I was letting myself become something else because the thing I loved was taken away.

22:52.993 --> 22:57.202
But what I can see now is that that injury was a limp that God gave me.

22:57.634 --> 23:01.219
God touched the socket of the thing that I leaned on most.

23:01.519 --> 23:05.044
He dislocated my primary source of false identity.

23:05.424 --> 23:11.092
And even now, decades later, if I push it on a runner, I push it on a bike rider, something happens, I feel my knees again.

23:11.152 --> 23:14.957
I just remember the lengths that God was willing to go to redirect me.

23:15.858 --> 23:18.341
Suddenly, I couldn't run in the same direction anymore.

23:19.142 --> 23:21.545
Jacob's limp meant that he couldn't outrun conflict.

23:21.986 --> 23:23.848
My limp meant that I couldn't outrun calling.

23:24.469 --> 23:25.170
What is yours mean?

23:26.082 --> 23:28.546
Some of you, you're here, and your limp, it isn't dramatic.

23:28.566 --> 23:29.527
It's not visible.

23:30.148 --> 23:30.669
It's subtle.

23:31.070 --> 23:32.332
It's a failed startup.

23:32.372 --> 23:33.553
It's a missed promotion.

23:33.613 --> 23:35.677
It's a relationship that didn't work out.

23:35.697 --> 23:39.563
It's a diagnosis you haven't told anybody about, and you're not sure what next steps are.

23:39.583 --> 23:40.504
It's a closed door.

23:40.764 --> 23:43.529
It's a season that didn't follow the script you'd written.

23:44.390 --> 23:45.391
And you didn't wrestle with God.

23:45.532 --> 23:46.393
You just pivoted.

23:46.413 --> 23:47.855
You just retreated to the next thing.

23:48.917 --> 23:50.719
But maybe that thing wasn't random.

23:50.740 --> 23:55.026
Maybe it was God limiting your ability to run from Him because

23:55.106 --> 23:59.011
limping with God is better than running on your own.

24:00.272 --> 24:06.119
Maybe God is calling you right now to go slower with Him than faster on your own.

24:06.139 --> 24:10.684
I think we've gotten so good at running so fast in the wrong direction.

24:11.445 --> 24:20.035
And sometimes, the most loving thing that God can do for me, maybe for you too, is take the very thing that we're using to avoid Him away.

24:21.116 --> 24:22.418
The limp is mercy.

24:22.754 --> 24:24.376
The limp keeps us close.

24:24.756 --> 24:29.441
The limp dismantles the version of us that can succeed without him, without surrender.

24:30.302 --> 24:33.565
And baptism is this regular, beautiful reminder of that.

24:34.686 --> 24:42.594
That we've stopped pretending, that we've let God in, that we don't enter the water strong, we enter it honestly, that we don't come in flexing, that we come in limping.

24:43.075 --> 24:43.936
And here's the good news.

24:44.736 --> 24:47.759
The limp doesn't disqualify you from God's plan.

24:47.819 --> 24:50.322
It actually positions you perfectly right in the middle of it.

24:51.042 --> 24:54.627
Jacob, he limped into the future as Israel, this new name.

24:55.408 --> 24:58.332
I limped off of a football field and into a calling that I couldn't see yet.

24:59.254 --> 25:01.036
And some of you, you're limping right now.

25:01.737 --> 25:07.485
And you think that it means you lost, but maybe it means you finally stopped running.

25:08.587 --> 25:13.554
Now, I want to be clear, not all limps that you and I experience are because we're running in the wrong direction.

25:14.146 --> 25:18.392
Not all limps that we're experiencing are a loving father giving you and me supernatural correction.

25:18.773 --> 25:26.784
Some of the pain and challenges and discomfort and atrocities that you face have nothing to do with choices you've made, but God can use them too.

25:27.765 --> 25:32.011
And when we stop running, God is ready to do His best work.

25:33.313 --> 25:39.762
That gives us, these us to our third benefit of staying in the fight, which is the fight brings a change of identity.

25:40.258 --> 25:41.619
Look back at verse 27.

25:41.639 --> 25:43.962
The wrestling match is winding down.

25:44.462 --> 25:46.365
The sun is about to come up.

25:46.805 --> 25:48.587
Jacob is out of resources.

25:48.687 --> 25:54.133
His hip is dislocated and he's clinging to God saying, I will not let you go unless you bless me.

25:54.153 --> 25:55.714
Remember Jacob, clinger.

25:56.856 --> 26:00.339
And then the man asks a piercing, terrifying question.

26:00.840 --> 26:03.583
What is your name?

26:04.344 --> 26:06.546
Now in that culture, the question really was, who are you?

26:07.330 --> 26:17.542
Now, if you remember Jacob's backstory from earlier at all, the last time that someone had asked Jacob what is your name was an aging dying father he was lying to.

26:18.143 --> 26:21.648
His dad was asking him who he was and he lies and says Esau.

26:21.688 --> 26:26.473
But here in this time, man, he can't do that anymore.

26:26.493 --> 26:30.638
With his dad, he wore a mask to steal a blessing, but now he can't lie.

26:30.699 --> 26:32.541
He can't lie to the Almighty in the dirt.

26:32.561 --> 26:33.522
He's too close.

26:34.146 --> 26:37.089
To get the true blessing this time, Jacob has to tell the truth.

26:37.109 --> 26:38.571
He has to confess his true nature.

26:38.931 --> 26:40.413
When God asks, what is your name?

26:40.473 --> 26:42.115
Jacob finally stops pretending.

26:42.135 --> 26:42.775
He tells the truth.

26:42.795 --> 26:43.596
He says, I'm Jacob.

26:43.977 --> 26:44.697
I'm the deceiver.

26:44.777 --> 26:45.799
I'm the grasper.

26:45.859 --> 26:46.559
I'm the runner.

26:46.579 --> 26:49.623
I'm the one that's been doing this year after year after year of my life.

26:49.923 --> 26:51.345
And look at how God responds.

26:51.965 --> 26:52.726
He doesn't shame him.

26:53.687 --> 26:56.730
He doesn't say, I know you're a mess, dude.

26:58.572 --> 27:03.858
He says, your name shall no longer be called Jacob, but Israel.

27:04.610 --> 27:08.897
for you have striven with God and with men and have prevailed.

27:09.978 --> 27:15.787
God gives him a brand new name, really a new identity, Israel, which means wrestles with God.

27:16.328 --> 27:26.344
God loved this broken limping exhausted hustler so much that he names his entire chosen people, the nation itself, after a midnight wrestling match with him.

27:26.444 --> 27:27.305
Isn't that wild?

27:27.666 --> 27:30.290
What God can do when we embrace the limp.

27:31.362 --> 27:34.607
This is the beauty of the gospel, the good news of Jesus.

27:35.088 --> 27:44.642
That when you finally stop running, when your ram crashes, when your system is on overload, when you finally confess who you really are, God doesn't remove you from his plan.

27:45.503 --> 27:46.124
He renames you.

27:46.144 --> 27:49.028
He gives you a new identity right in the middle of it.

27:49.829 --> 27:52.714
Jacob wrestled with God in the dark and walked away with a limp.

27:53.315 --> 28:00.946
And I'd love to tell you that after this interaction, Jacob's a changed man and he's just night and day better the rest of his life, but he still fails.

28:01.762 --> 28:02.683
He still falls short.

28:03.023 --> 28:05.906
He's still being shaped by God day by day.

28:06.627 --> 28:13.253
Jacob was like us, imperfectly pursuing God and needing Him just as much today as yesterday.

28:13.913 --> 28:19.138
But centuries later, after Jacob dies, God came down in the dark again.

28:19.178 --> 28:22.221
This time, Jesus didn't come to wrestle us.

28:22.301 --> 28:23.803
He came to wrestle for us.

28:23.823 --> 28:26.245
He came to fight for us on the cross.

28:27.006 --> 28:29.548
He would take the ultimate blow that we deserved.

28:30.309 --> 28:31.730
He looked at our sin.

28:32.482 --> 28:36.447
our exhaustion, our deception, our failure.

28:37.468 --> 28:42.014
He allowed himself to be broken so that we could be finally made whole.

28:42.034 --> 28:46.319
He didn't just take your, in my limp, he took the death that all of us deserve.

28:46.980 --> 28:58.034
And then three days later, he rose again to offer you and me, not just a better life with him today, not easier, but better and more purposeful with him today, but an eternity with him.

28:58.530 --> 29:04.097
And that's what we prepare to celebrate at Easter, that because he has new life, we have it too.

29:05.098 --> 29:06.580
That's exactly what baptism is.

29:07.241 --> 29:10.685
It's the physical declaration of a new identity.

29:11.466 --> 29:19.196
You leave your old behind, deceiver, addict, failure, hustler, the one who runs, you leave all that at the bottom of the water.

29:19.897 --> 29:27.186
And you come up with a new identity, a personal faith made public, beloved, forgiven child of God.

29:28.130 --> 29:32.979
Some of you came in today, exhausted from wrestling, maybe exhausted from her treating.

29:33.600 --> 29:39.751
You've been trying to upgrade your ram, outrun your past, or maybe fight your way to peace, and your system is crashing.

29:40.553 --> 29:51.954
And God is wrestling with you right now, not to hurt you, but to get you to finally yield, not to run, not to even give up, but to let God win.

29:52.674 --> 30:01.634
So if you're ready for a hard reboot today, if you're ready to stop running and finally let God win the wrestling match, I wanna lead you in a simple prayer.

30:02.856 --> 30:07.186
You don't have to have everything cleaned up in your life, you don't have to be perfect, you just have to be honest.

30:07.426 --> 30:09.649
I'm gonna pray this prayer a few words at a time.

30:09.729 --> 30:12.552
For some of you, you're ready to make this decision to follow Jesus.

30:12.593 --> 30:14.175
You pray these words out loud with me.

30:14.295 --> 30:26.390
And if you're a follower of Jesus, even if you've been a follower of Jesus for decades, I'm gonna ask that you pray these words out loud with me as well as a reminder of the centrality and the primacy of God's grace in your life too.

30:26.871 --> 30:29.594
And I'm gonna do one other thing that's gonna require you to move.

30:29.634 --> 30:31.757
So in about five seconds, I'm gonna ask you to do something.

30:31.777 --> 30:32.678
Everybody locked in?

30:33.539 --> 30:35.922
I'm gonna ask you right now, as we pray,

30:36.002 --> 30:41.227
to stand up at all of our campuses, and we're gonna pray together while you're standing.

30:44.150 --> 30:49.996
Would you close your eyes, and if you're praying this for the first time, or you're reminding yourself after decades of following Jesus, pray these words with me.

30:50.476 --> 30:51.637
Jesus, I'm tired of running.

30:54.200 --> 30:55.701
I lay down all of my masks.

30:58.284 --> 31:00.066
I've been wrestling, but today I yield.

31:03.249 --> 31:04.690
Forgive me my sins.

31:06.658 --> 31:08.921
and forgive me for trying to run my life on my own.

31:12.386 --> 31:14.168
Thank you for fighting for me on the cross.

31:17.292 --> 31:19.415
Today I leave my old identity behind.

31:19.435 --> 31:27.186
I receive your forgiveness and a new identity in you.

31:29.489 --> 31:33.394
From this day on, I choose to follow you.

31:35.106 --> 31:39.764
Teach me to walk in your ways and at your pace.

31:41.391 --> 31:43.881
In Jesus' name.

31:43.901 --> 31:44.242
Amen.

31:45.154 --> 31:48.757
across all of our campuses, there are people that just made that prayer for the very first time.

31:49.338 --> 31:54.322
And for some of you, you've sensed it, like God's calling you to take a step and to get baptized today.

31:54.342 --> 31:55.283
I've already told you this.

31:56.003 --> 31:59.186
There's everything that we could possibly have ready for you, we have ready.

31:59.747 --> 32:09.455
And in the back of whatever room you're in, at whatever campus you're at, there are people waiting for you that would love to connect with you, that would love to show you to a place you can change, that would love to pray with you.

32:09.755 --> 32:15.140
And so if God's calling you to do that, and just a second, I'm gonna pray, during that prayer or after it, just head to the back of the room,

32:15.120 --> 32:17.223
from at the campus you're at and talk to them.

32:18.205 --> 32:22.911
Don't leave today without taking that step if God's calling you to take it.

32:23.953 --> 32:24.734
Would you pray with me?

32:25.956 --> 32:26.877
God, thank you so much.

32:27.739 --> 32:35.430
Thank you for the profound gift that you are still working, that you are still rescuing and redeeming, retreating, and running people.

32:36.571 --> 32:43.762
Thank you, God, that wrestling with you is still an option, that your love for us is inexhaustible.

32:44.386 --> 32:48.912
that none of us can outrun your grace, your love, your compassion, and your mercy.

32:49.773 --> 32:55.700
Thank you for the lives that you've already touched this weekend, for the lives that have gone from death to life.

32:57.363 --> 33:03.150
Would you even now help us to celebrate as your church, as people make that decision public?

33:04.071 --> 33:06.354
In Jesus' name, amen.

